definition.value: A fatty acid ester resulting from the formal condensation of the hydroxy group of phytol with the carboxy group of any fatty acid.
A fatty acid phytyl ester resulting from the formal condensation of the hydroxy group of phytol with the carboxy group of hexadecanoic acid.
An agonist that binds to and activates somatostatin receptors.
A hexane-2,5-diol with R-configuration at both the C-2 and C-5 centres.

An L-proline derivative that is L-proline substituted by a carboxymethyl group at position 3 and a (2E)-6-methylhepta-2,5-dien-2-yl group at position 4. It is produced by the red algal Chondria armata.
A fatty acid phytyl ester resulting from the formal condensation of the hydroxy group of phytol with the carboxy group of tetradecanoic acid.
A fatty acid phytyl ester resulting from the formal condensation of the hydroxy group of phytol with the carboxy group of dodecanoic acid.
A fatty acid phytyl ester resulting from the formal condensation of the hydroxy group of phytol with the carboxy group of decanoic acid.
A fatty acid phytyl ester resulting from the formal condensation of the hydroxy group of phytol with the carboxy group of all-cis-7,10,13-hexadecatrienoic acid.
An oxysterol that is cholesterol substituted at position 26 by a hydroxy group.

A 4-hydroxy-5-(4-hydroxybenzylidene)-3-(4-hydroxyphenyl)furan-2(5H)-one in which the double bond adopts a Z-configuration. It is a marine metabolite isolated from the fungus Aspergillus terreus and exhibits antiviral activity.
A dimethoxyflavone that is luteolin in which the hydroxy groups at positions 7 and 3' are replaced by methoxy groups.
An N-acyl-L-arginine resulting from the formal condensation of the alpha-amino group of L-arginine with one of the carboxy groups of succinic acid
